	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				First off, I'm only a level 5 enchanter, and this is my first caster-type character, as I prefered to start with a tank.  Bad idea, I decided, by the time he was level 28.  I figured I'd make a caster to occupy those times when I can't beg my way into a group with my tank.<BR>
<BR>
I love my character now, and most of all, I love mesmerizing things.  At the present time my casting time is a bit long to mezz something by the time that two are on me, though I've found using color flux to buy myself an extra second or two seems to work well.<BR>
<BR>
I digress.  In every experience with mesmerize I have, when the spell wore off the creature was no longer agro on me.  Nor was it agro on others.<BR>
<BR>
In one case, a low level paladin got jumped by two pixie tricksters.  He killed one, and noticed the other, but his life was quite low.  You yelled for help, and I began casting Mez, and told him to stop attacking NOW!<BR>
<BR>
He did, and stared puzzled at the pixie for a few seconds.  When it finally came back around it calmly fluttered off, as if nothing had ever happened.<BR>
<BR>
Perhaps the success of the memory blur part of mesmerization has to do with the amount of damage done before you mez it.  In every case that I've used it, it was just to buy myself time to run, or time to cast a long spell without getting chewed on.<BR>
<BR>
In summary, I think that the memory part of mesmerization may be a little hit or miss.  It almost has to be, seeings as how enchanters get a memory blur spell.  You figure if you can use mesmerization and get the same effect + temporary stun then who would even bother buying memory blur?<BR>
<BR>
Any more comments appreciated<BR>
<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
